sentences: Cory Branan (born December 15, 1974) is an American singer-songwriter from Mississippi.
In his early 20s he began to explore the music of singer-songwriter John Prine, which led to Branan writing his own songs, which he began performing at open mic nights at Memphis' Daily Planet.
Although initially self-released in 2001, Branan re-released his debut full-length album, The Hell You Say, on MADJACK Records on October 8, 2002.

In 2003, Branan made his TV network debut playing the song, "Miss Ferguson" on The David Letterman Show.
In 2006, Branan released his sophomore effort, 12 Songs on March 21, 2006, on MADJACK Records.

In 2011, Branan signed with Bloodshot Records.
Six years after his prior record, he released Mutt on May 22, 2012.

The album, produced by Paul Ebersold and recorded over the period of three days in Nashville at The Sound Kitchen, features contributions by Craig Finn and Steve Selvidge of The Hold Steady, Tim Easton, Caitlin Rose, Austin Lucas, and Jason Isbell.
The record was listed by Rolling Stone magazine as one of the top 40 country records of 2014.
Branan released his fifth album, Adios, on April 7, 2017.
Rolling Stone listed it as the 27th Best Country and Americana Album of 2017.
In 2021, Blue Élan Records announced they had signed Branan to their label, with a new album expected to be released early 2022.
